    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p>
                    <bibl><ptr target="#jmr1996"/>, p. <citedRange>40</citedRange>, pl. <citedRange>XIV</citedRange></bibl>, 
                    whence <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>46.2222</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#chamoux2000"/>, pp. <citedRange>109-114</citedRange></bibl>, 
                    whence <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>50.1651</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#GVCyr"/> <citedRange>015</citedRange></bibl>.
                    Cf. <bibl><ptr target="#jmr1998"/>, pp. <citedRange>479-480</citedRange></bibl>.
                </p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                    <lg met="elegiac couplet">
                        <lb n="1"/><l n="1" met="hexameter">
                            <seg real="++|+--|+--|++|+--|+-"><persName type="divine" ref="#Mousae"><name nymRef="#Μοῦσα">Μουσάων</name></persName> <w lemma="θεράπων">θεράποντα</w> καὶ
                            <persName type="divine" ref="#Heracles"><name nymRef="#Ἡρακλῆς">Ἡρακλῆος</name></persName> <w lemma="ἑταῖρος">ἑταῖρον</w>
                            <space quantity="1" unit="character"/></seg></l>
                        <lb n="2"/><l n="2" met="pentameter">
                            <seg real="+--|++|+|+--|+--|+"><persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#Μυρτίλος">Μυρτίλον</name></persName> 
                            <w lemma="ὅδε">ἥδ'</w> <w lemma="εὐνή">εὐνὴ</w> <w lemma="λαϊνέος">λαϊνέη</w> <w lemma="κατέχω">κατέχει</w>
                            <space quantity="1" unit="character"/></seg></l>
                    </lg>
                    <lg met="elegiac couplet">
                        <lb n="3"/><l n="3" met="hexameter">
                            <seg real="+--|+--|+--|+--|+--|+-"><w lemma="ὅς1" type="relative">ᾦ</w> <w lemma="κανών">κανόνες</w> τε <w lemma="πούς">πόδες</w> τε <w lemma="διηνεκής">διηνεκέως</w> 
                            <w lemma="μέλω">ἐμέλησ<supplied reason="lost">αν</supplied></w></seg></l>
                        <lb n="4"/>
                        <l n="4" met="pentameter">
                            <seg real="+--|+--|+|+--|+--|+"><w lemma="πεντάεθλον">πενταέθλων</w> <w lemma="μελέτη">μελέτης</w> <w lemma="γράμμα">γράμματι</w> 
                            <w lemma="κήδομαι">κη<supplied reason="lost">δομένῳ</supplied></w></seg></l>
                    </lg>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p>
                    <app loc="4">
                        <lem resp="#chamoux2000">γράμματι κη<supplied reason="lost">δομένῳ</supplied></lem>
                            <rdg resp="#jmr1996">γραμματικῆ<supplied reason="lost">ς θ' ἅμ' ἔην</supplied></rdg>
                            <rdg resp="#jmr1996">γραμματικῆ<supplied reason="lost">ς τε γὰρ ἦν</supplied></rdg>
                        
                    </app>
                </p>     
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr" source="#chamoux2000">
                <p>Serviteur des Muses et compagnon d'Héraclès,</p>
                <p>tel était Myrtilos qui repose dans cette tombe de pierre.</p>
                <p>Il n'a pas cessé de donner tous ses soins aux règles et aux pieds</p>
                <p>en consacrant un poème à la pratique du pentathle.</p>
                <note>trad. Fr. Chamoux</note>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en" source="#jmr1996">
                <p>Servant of the Muses and companion of Heracles,</p>
                <p>Myrtilos is constrained by this bed of stone.</p>
                <p>The rules and feet were his constant care</p>
                <p>and he produced a poem about the pentathlon practice (J.M. Reynolds' translation with some changes).</p>
                
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
                <p>Servitore delle Muse e compagno di Eracle,</p>
                <p>Myrtilos questo letto di pietra trattiene.</p>
                <p>A lui ininterrottamente stettero a cuore i metri e i piedi:</p>
                <p>dedicò un poema alla pratica del pentathlon.</p>
            </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>Reynolds suspected that Myrtilos' tomb stood inside the <rs type="monuList" ref="https://www.slsgazetteer.org/1124">Gymnasium</rs>, which would explain that the stone was
                reused in the nearby <rs type="monuList" ref="https://www.slsgazetteer.org/1128">Byzantine 'fortress'</rs>, more easily than if it was brought from one of the necropoles outside the city walls.</p>
                <p>In Chamoux' view, the <foreign xml:lang="grc">γράμμα</foreign> was a didactical poem about the pentathlon; of course Myrtilos would also have composed his own epitaph.</p>
                <p>Metrical analysis: two elegiac couplets.</p>
            </div></body>
